	<main>
		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="spiny urchins on a coral reef" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-urchin-resoration-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">With spikes as long as knitting needles, long-spined sea urchins may look like underwater villains, but their appetite for algae makes them the unsung heroes of Caribbean reefs. Photo courtesy of the University of Florida</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Very Hungry Urchins</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Researchers are restoring the Caribbean’s surprising, spiky custodians, which gobble up the algae smothering coral reefs.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/lisa-s-gardiner/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Lisa S. Gardiner</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						July 30, 2024 | 1,900 words, about 9 minutes
